contents.name: EA modeler
contents.description: A role, assigned to an actor, requiring the creation, maintenance, or expansion of an enterprise architecture model.

contents.name: EAM consumer
contents.description: An actor who is expected to independently interact with a specific enterprise architecture model, on the belief that this interaction will contribute to some cognitive goal of theirs.

contents.name: EAM audience
contents.description: A set of enterprise architecture model consumers that are each expected to independently interact with a specific enterprise architecture model.

contents.name: World
contents.description: The state of things as they are, outside and independent of any observer.

contents.name: System universe
contents.description: The “universe of items” that harbors the system that is the subject of the enterprise architecture model; the context in which that system exists.

contents.name: EAM universe
contents.description: The “universe of discourse” that covers the part of the enterprise and its surroundings that fully envelopes the system that is the subject of the enterprise architecture model, including all parts of the enterprise that themselves change if the system is changed.

contents.name: Architecture concept
contents.description: A knowledge unit (characteristics, meaning, and a term or label) that comprises the enterprise architecture of a system.

contents.name: Architecture concept*
contents.description: A knowledge unit that comprises the enterprise architecture of a system, or part thereof, as it is learned by a stakeholder from an enterprise architecture model.

contents.name: System
contents.description: An item of interest within the enterprise that is the subject of an enterprise architecture model, whereby “item” can be anything from ideas and objects to processes and information, or aggregations thereof.

contents.name: EAM consumer goal
contents.description: A cognitive goal, pursued by an enterprise architecture model consumer, connected with the enterprise architecture that the enterprise architecture model attempts to capture.

contents.name: EAM audience goal set
contents.description: The aggregated set of enterprise architecture model consumer goals that an enterprise architecture model is intended to contribute to.

contents.name: Correspondence
contents.description: The degree to which the interpretation of an enterprise architecture model by an enterprise architecture consumer agrees with the architecture concept as conceived by the enterprise architecture modeler

contents.name: Actor
contents.description: A person, organization, or system that has one or more roles that initiates or interacts with activities.

contents.name: EAM
contents.description: A social artifact reflecting an enterprise architecture, intended to cost-effectively pursue a particular cognitive objective in support of a particular audience.

contents.name: EAM content
contents.description: The information that reflects the enterprise architecture that an enterprise architecture modeler attempts to capture.

contents.name: EAM embodiment
contents.description: The perceptible form of an enterprise architecture model that carries the enterprise architecture model content, and in doing so expresses the architecture concept.

contents.name: EAM objective
contents.description: The objective that an enterprise architecture modeler needs to meet, in order for the enterprise architecture model to provide the maximum contribution to the goals of the enterprise architecture model audience.

contents.name: EAM quality judgment
contents.description: The judgment by an enterprise architecture model consumer of the ease with which they can employ the information in the enterprise architecture model in the pursuit of their goal, and the extent to which their understanding of this information actually contributes to those goals.

contents.name: EAM quality
contents.description: The aggregation of all enterprise architecture model quality attributes.

properties.name: EAM Quality attribute 1
properties.description: The aggregation of all enterprise architecture model quality attributes, each of which is a characteristic that contributes to an enterprise architecture model quality judgment..
